pkg rig v1
  desc "AI agent and tool abstractions — Rig SDK patterns"
  author "VEIL"

  # ─── Tool Constructs ────────────────────────────────────────────────────

  construct Tool
    kw tool
    mt fn
    desc "An AI-callable tool with typed args, schema, and async execution"
    has
      fn[]
    visual
      icon "🔧"
      color "#10b981"
      label "Tool"
    ann
      desc: "Tool description shown to the LLM" value
    group tools

  construct Agent
    kw agent
    mt fn
    desc "An LLM agent with a preamble, model, and registered tools"
    visual
      icon "🤖"
      color "#6366f1"
      label "Agent"
    ann
      model: "LLM model identifier" value
      preamble: "System prompt for the agent" value
    group agents

  construct ToolSet
    kw tool_set
    mt group
    desc "Organizational container for related tools"
    contains
      Tool[]
      Agent[]
    visual
      icon "🧰"
      color "#059669"
      label "Tool Set"
    group tools

  # ─── Declared types ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────

  declare
    enum ToolError
      ToolCallError(Str)
      InvalidArgs(Str)
      Internal(Str)

    struct ToolDefinition
      name: Str
      description: Str
      parameters: Json

  prompt
    You are writing VEIL code using the Rig layer (AI agent/tool abstractions).

    ## Overview
    This layer provides constructs for defining AI-callable tools and LLM agents
    following the Rig SDK patterns. Tools are typed async functions with JSON
    schema descriptions. Agents combine a model, system prompt, and tool set.

    ## Constructs
    - `tool` (fn) — an AI-callable function with typed args and description
    - `agent` (fn) — an LLM agent with preamble, model, and tools
    - `tool_set` (group) — organizational container for related tools/agents

    ## Constraints
    - You MUST annotate every tool with `@desc("...")` because the LLM uses
      this description to decide when to call the tool.
    - You MUST annotate agents with `@model("...")` and `@preamble("...")`
      because these configure the underlying LLM.
    - You SHOULD group related tools into a `tool_set` because agents
      register entire sets, not individual tools.
    - You MUST NOT perform side effects in tool argument validation because
      the schema is evaluated before execution.

    ## Patterns
    ```
    tool_set WeatherTools
      tool GetWeather
        @desc("Get current weather for a city")
        input
          city: Str
          units: Str
        step execute
          response = weather_api.get!(city, units)
          ret response

      agent WeatherAssistant
        @model("gpt-4")
        @preamble("You help users check weather conditions.")
    ```

    ## Common Mistakes
    - Wrong: Tool without @desc — the LLM won't know when to call it.
    - Wrong: Complex business logic inside a tool — tools should be thin
      wrappers that call domain services.
    - Right: Tools delegate to domain handlers, agents compose tools.
